  "prompt": "Programming Languages: What was the first REPL?",
  "response": "The first **REPL** (Read-Eval-Print Loop) was introduced with the **Lisp** programming language in the late 1950s. Lisp, developed by John McCarthy at MIT, was one of the earliest high-level programming languages and is widely recognized as the first to implement an interactive programming environment.\n\n### Key Features of Lisp's REPL:\n1. **Read**: The interpreter reads user input (expressions or code).\n2. **Eval**: It evaluates the input and computes the result.\n3. **Print**: It displays the result to the user.\n4. **Loop**: The process repeats, allowing for interactive programming.\n\nThis approach was revolutionary at the time because it allowed programmers to write, test, and debug code interactively, rather than relying solely on batch processing. The REPL became a defining feature of Lisp and inspired many later programming languages, including Python, Ruby, and others, to adopt similar interactive environments.",
